# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: alex-dow
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:alex-dow/alex-davison-bailey] Bailey was born in what is now Salem Lakes, Wisconsin, son of Eugene M.
[src:alex-dow/alex-davison-bailey] He obtained his BSc in Mechanical Engineering in 1903 from the Lewis Institute in Chicago, now Illinois Institute of Technology.
[src:alex-dow/alex-davison-bailey] Before his graduation Bailey had started his career as draftsman at the U.S Wind Engine and Pump Company in Batavia, Illinois, and had been trouble man at the Evanston Heating Co. in Evanston, Illinois.
[src:alex-dow/alex-davison-bailey] After his graduation Bailey started his lifelong career at the Chicago Edison Co., soon to be Commonwealth Edison.
[src:alex-dow/alex-davison-bailey] From 1903 to 1905 he started as draftsman, from 1906 to 1916 he was assistant chief engineer at Fisk Street Station, and another chief engineer.
[src:alex-dow/alex-davison-bailey] From 1921 to 1932 he was superintendent of generating stations of the company, and in 1933 appointed assistant chief operating engineer.
[src:alex-dow/alex-davison-bailey] From 1936 to 1942 he was chief operating engineer and manager of the Super Power department.
[src:alex-dow/alex-davison-bailey] The last years ten years at the company he was vice-president in charge of operations and engineering.
[src:alex-dow/alex-davison-bailey] He retired on February 1, 1952 after 48 years of service.
[src:alex-dow/alex-davison-bailey] In 1942 Bailey had been awarded the Honorary Doctor of Science by the Northwestern University.
[src:alex-dow/alex-dow] Dow was born in Glasgow, Scotland as son of William Dow, a blacksmith, and Jean (Keppy) Dow in 1862.
[src:alex-dow/alex-dow] He emigrated to the US in 1882 at the age of twenty.
[src:alex-dow/alex-dow] In 1893 Dow was appointed the first plant manager of the first municipally owned power plant in Detroit, and electrical engineer for the city of Detroit.
[src:alex-dow/alex-dow] The power plant had been built as a result of Hazen Pingree's efforts to break the power of corporations over Detroit City politics.
[src:alex-dow/alex-dow] It was during this time that Henry Ford worked under Dow at one of the Detroit Edison substations.
[src:alex-dow/alex-dow] Dow took Ford with him to the 1896 annual convention of the Association of Edison Illuminating Companies being held that year in New York City.
[src:alex-dow/alex-dow] It was at this convention that Dow introduced Ford to Thomas Edison, the meeting with, and encouragement from, the great scientist becoming a great inspiration to Ford in completing his first car.
[src:alex-dow/alex-dow] Dow was appointed water commissioner for the city of Detroit in 1916-1921 and again in 1925-1932.
[src:alex-dow/alex-dow] In 1932, he was made the president of Detroit Edison and served until 1940.
[src:alex-dow/alex-dow] He was elected president of the American Society of Mechanical Engineers for the 1928-1929 year.
[src:alex-dow/alex-dow] He was a member of the American Society of Mechanical Engineers, American Society of Civil Engineers, American Institute of Electrical Engineers, Institute of Electrical Engineers (Great Britain), Institute of Mechanical Engineers (Great Britain).
[src:alex-dow/alex-dow] Dow also served as the President of The Engineering Society of Detroit from 1900-1901.
[src:alex-dow/alexander-crombie-humphreys] Humphreys was born in Edinburgh, Scotland on 30 March 1851 to Edward Rupert Humphreys, an English classical scholar and profound educator, and Margaret McNutt of Prince Edward Island.
[src:alex-dow/alexander-crombie-humphreys] He attended his father's school in Boston after coming to the United States in 1859.
[src:alex-dow/alexander-crombie-humphreys] At the age of fourteen he received an appointment and passed preliminary entrance exams for the United States Naval Academy before the academy discovered he was too young to complete entrance.
[src:alex-dow/alexander-crombie-humphreys] He instead began working for insurance companies and was made Secretary-Treasurer of the New York Guaranty and Indemnity Company by 1872, he became superintendent shortly thereafter.
[src:alex-dow/alexander-crombie-humphreys] He later became superintendent of the Bayonne and Greenville Gas Light Company and attended Stevens Institute of Technology earning his degree in mechanical engineering; he graduated in 1881.
[src:alex-dow/alexander-crombie-humphreys] In 1892 he founded Humphreys & Glasgow, Engineering, London and New York with Arthur G.
[src:alex-dow/alexander-crombie-humphreys] Humphreys continued his career with the Pintsch Lighting Company of New York, the United Gas Improvement Company, and the Weisbach Incandescent Gas Company.
[src:alex-dow/alexander-crombie-humphreys] In April 1872 he married Miss Eva Guillandeu of Bergen Point, NJ.
[src:alex-dow/alexander-crombie-humphreys] They had three children in total: Harold, Crombie and Dorothy Caroline Humphreys-Turnbull.
[src:alex-dow/alexander-crombie-humphreys] In memory of his son Harold, who was also the first son of a Stevens alumnus to graduate from the college, he endowed the Harold Humphreys Scholarship in 1902.
[src:alex-dow/alexander-crombie-humphreys] In memory of Crombie, who drowned with Harold in the Nile in 1901, the Crombie Humphreys Scholarship in 1904.
[src:alex-dow/alexander-crombie-humphreys] In 1927, Alexander Crombie Humphreys lost a battle with cancer.
[src:alex-dow/alexander-crombie-humphreys] His death came two years after serving as President of his Alma mater for a quarter of a century, and chairman of the board of trustees for two years.
[src:alex-dow/alexander-crombie-humphreys] The only immediate family member to outlive him was his daughter.
[src:alex-dow/alexander-crombie-humphreys] Following the death of Henry Morton in 1902, the board of trustees of Stevens Institute of Technology unanimously called upon Humphreys to serve his Alma mater as president.
[src:alex-dow/alexander-crombie-humphreys] Prior to his presidency, Humphreys was elected a trustee of the institute on 23 December 1891 and served as chair of the Stevens Alumni Association from 1883 to 1886.
[src:alex-dow/alexander-crombie-humphreys] Humphreys developed the institute as one of the first technical schools in the United States.
[src:alex-dow/alexander-crombie-humphreys] During a dinner following his inauguration, Colonel Edwin A.
[src:alex-dow/alexander-crombie-humphreys] Stevens, Jr., son of the school's founder Edwin A.
[src:alex-dow/alexander-crombie-humphreys] Stevens, presented the institute with a plot of land on which to construct a dormitory.
[src:alex-dow/alexander-crombie-humphreys] Upon assuming the office of President, Humphreys requested of Andrew Carnegie the financial support to construct a new building.
[src:alex-dow/alexander-crombie-humphreys] He followed this with an address to the Board of Trustees urging construction of the Morton Laboratory of Chemistry, a dormitory, a gymnasium and library – a "crying need of the Institute".
[src:alex-dow/alexander-crombie-humphreys] As a homage to his predecessor, Humphreys campaigned for the creation of the Morton Memorial Chemistry Laboratory and commissioned a book on Stevens' founding and its early years to be named in his honor.
[src:alex-dow/alexander-crombie-humphreys] These initiatives were but foreshadowing of the growth Humphreys would bring to Stevens.
[src:alex-dow/alexander-crombie-humphreys] By 1924 the campus grew from just over a city block to 23-acres, enrollment quadrupled and endowment grew to $2,864,000 (from $384,800 when Humprheys took office).
[src:alex-dow/alexander-crombie-humphreys] That year also marked the successful end of the "Million Dollar Campaign", which had attracted donations from alumni as well as George Eastman and Edward Harkness.
[src:alex-dow/alexander-crombie-humphreys] In 1909, Stevens seized the opportunity to acquire Castle Point from Richard Stevens inclusive of the prominent Stevens Family Castle constructed in 1853; the purchase was primarily funded by the Carnegie Foundation and John D.
[src:alex-dow/alexander-crombie-humphreys] This came within months of acquiring the land adjacent to present-day 8th street upon which fraternity houses were constructed that stand to this day.
[src:alex-dow/alexander-crombie-humphreys] In 1960 the Institute expanded again and constructed two residence halls, one of which bared his name.
[src:alex-dow/alexander-crombie-humphreys] During the growth of the institute, Alexander C.
[src:alex-dow/alexander-crombie-humphreys] Humphreys felt it important to impart engineering students with a sense of business – a tool that would be essential in their success in all lines of manufacturing.
[src:alex-dow/alexander-crombie-humphreys] He began teaching the first courses on this topic in 1903 and is regarded as the father of Engineering Economics.
[src:alex-dow/alexander-crombie-humphreys] To honor his contributions, Stevens Institute of Technology endows an Alexander Crombie Humphreys Chair in Economics of Engineering.
[src:alex-dow/alexander-crombie-humphreys] During the dinner of his inauguration, Humphreys announced that one of his ambitions was to start an Honor System at Stevens to cover academic work.
[src:alex-dow/alexander-crombie-humphreys] Humphreys was very adamant that the creation of such a system come from the students and on the first page of the first issue of the school newspaper "The Stute" appeared an article written by a junior urging the implementation of such.
[src:alex-dow/alexander-crombie-humphreys] By 1908 the students created a self run Honor Board who was charged with investigating cases, bringing up charges, judging cases by a vote and recommend punishments to the faculty.
[src:alex-dow/alexander-crombie-humphreys] Upon Humphreys' recommendation, faculty were also required to abide by such a pledge in administering exams within Honor Board guidelines on the grounds that it is a "...proviso apply[ing] to the examiner as well as to the student".
[src:alex-dow/alexander-graham-christie] Christie was born in Manchester, Ontario, Canada to Peter Christie and Mary Honor (Graham) Christie.
[src:alex-dow/alexander-graham-christie] He obtained his MSc in mechanical engineering at the School of Practical Science at the University of Toronto in 1901.
[src:alex-dow/alexander-graham-christie] After his graduation Christie started as an apprentice in the engineering shop of the Westinghouse Machine Company.
[src:alex-dow/alexander-graham-christie] After the introduction of its first steam turbine, Christie specialized in that field.
[src:alex-dow/alexander-graham-christie] By 1909 he was research Assistant in Steam and Gas Engineering at the University of Wisconsin, and associate professor of Steam and Gas Engineering by 1914.
[src:alex-dow/alexander-graham-christie] In 1914 he moved to the Johns Hopkins University, where he became associate professor, and later Professor of Engineering until his retirement in 1948, and director of the McCoy College until 1953.
[src:alex-dow/alexander-graham-christie] In 1939-40 Christie served as president of the American Society of Mechanical Engineers.
[src:alex-dow/alexander-graham-christie] He was awarded the honorary doctor in engineering by the Stevens Institute of Technology in 1939, and by the Lehigh University in 1940.
[src:alex-dow/alexander-graham-christie] The American Society for Engineering Education awarded Christie the Lamme Gold Medal in 1948, and the first George Westinghouse Gold Medal for engineering by the ASME in 1953.
[src:alex-dow/alexander-graham-christie] At the Johns Hopkins Whiting school of Engineer an annual lecture is held on his behalf, the Alexander Graham Christie Lecture.
[src:alex-dow/ambrose-swasey] Swasey was born near Exeter, New Hampshire to Nathaniel and Abigail Swasey.
[src:alex-dow/ambrose-swasey] He apprenticed as a machinist at the Exeter Machine Works and was afterwards employed at Pratt & Whitney.
[src:alex-dow/ambrose-swasey] As his career progressed, he became a foreman in the gear-cutting section.
[src:alex-dow/ambrose-swasey] He developed a new technique for making gear-tooth cutters.
[src:alex-dow/ambrose-swasey] In 1880, he and Warner formed their eponymous firm, which quickly moved to Cleveland, Ohio.
[src:alex-dow/ambrose-swasey] Swasey would perform the engineering and machine development at this company.
[src:alex-dow/ambrose-swasey] The close friends Warner and Swasey built their homes next to each other on Euclid Avenue in Cleveland, a street that was known as "Millionaire's Row".
[src:alex-dow/ambrose-swasey] In addition to army ordnance contracts, the firm of Warner & Swasey became notable for their work on astronomical observatories and equipment.
[src:alex-dow/ambrose-swasey] The founders were interested in astronomy as an avocation, and in the field's quest for better optical telescopes, which was burgeoning at the time.
[src:alex-dow/ambrose-swasey] They also realized that obtaining contracts to build large astronomical observatories would provide publicity for their company.
[src:alex-dow/ambrose-swasey] In 1885, Swasey completed work at McCormick Observatory on the 45-foot dome, which was the largest in the world, and had a unique, 3 shutter design.
[src:alex-dow/ambrose-swasey] In 1887, Swasey built the mount for the 36-inch refracting telescope at Lick Observatory.
[src:alex-dow/ambrose-swasey] In 1898, he manufactured a dividing engine for the U.S.
[src:alex-dow/ambrose-swasey] Naval Observatory that was used to make the meridian circles.
[src:alex-dow/ambrose-swasey] Both the building and dome of the Dominion Astrophysical Observatory were made by Warner and Swasey Co.
[src:alex-dow/ambrose-swasey] Other observatory telescopes and components were built by the company at the Kenwood Observatory, Yerkes Observatory, Argentine National Observatory, the Swasey Observatory at Denison University, and the Case School of Applied Science Observatory.
[src:alex-dow/ambrose-swasey] From 1904 until 1905, he was the president of the American Society of Mechanical Engineers.
[src:alex-dow/ambrose-swasey] Both Warner and Swasey were amateur astronomers.
[src:alex-dow/ambrose-swasey] When they became trustees of the Case School of Applied Science, they donated to the school their private observatory, which they had built between their neighboring houses in East Cleveland.
[src:alex-dow/ambrose-swasey] Relocated to a new building, this became the Warner and Swasey Observatory.
[src:alex-dow/ambrose-swasey] The observatory maintained by the department today is still known by this name today.
[src:alex-dow/ambrose-swasey] Swasey Hall (1917, "懷士堂"), a red brick hall, is the landmark of Sun Yat-sen University, one of the top colleges in China.
[src:alex-dow/ambrose-swasey] It was named after Swasey for his USD$25000 donation to the then university Christian YMCA society hall.
[src:alex-dow/ambrose-swasey] The chimes in the chapel were included as a memorial to his wife, Lavinia Marston Swasey.
[src:alex-dow/ambrose-swasey] The Warner & Swasey Company he cofounded would continue until 1980, when it was acquired by Bendix Corporation.
[src:alex-dow/american-institute-of-electrical-engineers] The **American Institute of Electrical Engineers** (**AIEE**) was a United States–based organization of electrical engineers that existed from 1884 through 1962.
[src:alex-dow/american-institute-of-electrical-engineers] On January 1, 1963, it merged with the Institute of Radio Engineers (IRE) to form the Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers (IEEE).
[src:alex-dow/american-institute-of-electrical-engineers] The 1884 founders of the American Institute of Electrical Engineers (AIEE) included some of the most prominent inventors and innovators in the then new field of electrical engineering, among them Nikola Tesla, Thomas Alva Edison, Elihu Thomson, Edwin J.
[src:alex-dow/american-institute-of-electrical-engineers] Other notable AIEE presidents were Alexander Graham Bell (1891–1892), Charles Proteus Steinmetz (1901–1902), Bion J.
[src:alex-dow/american-institute-of-electrical-engineers] The first technical meeting of the AIEE was held during the International Electrical Exhibition of 1884 in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania, on October 7–8, at the Franklin Institute.
[src:alex-dow/american-institute-of-electrical-engineers] After several years of operating primarily in New York City, the AIEE authorized local sections in 1902.
[src:alex-dow/american-institute-of-electrical-engineers] These were first formed in the United States in Chicago and Ithaca, New York, in 1902, and then in other countries.
[src:alex-dow/american-institute-of-electrical-engineers] The first section outside the United States, established in 1903, was in Toronto, Canada.
[src:alex-dow/american-institute-of-electrical-engineers] AIEE's regional structure was soon complemented by a technical structure.
[src:alex-dow/american-institute-of-electrical-engineers] The first technical committee of AIEE, the High Voltage Transmission Committee, was formed in 1903.
[src:alex-dow/american-institute-of-electrical-engineers] Standardization work started in 1891 with the formation of a committee on units and standards, followed by a committee on standard wiring.
[src:alex-dow/american-institute-of-electrical-engineers] At the 50th anniversary of the organization, there were 10 women members, including Edith Clarke (associate member in 1923, member in 1933) and Mabel MacFerran Rockwell (associate member in 1928, member in 1935).
[src:alex-dow/american-institute-of-electrical-engineers] The formation of the AIEE Subcommittee on Large-Scale Computing in 1946 was considered a key milestone in the history of computer engineering, representing the first time that a professional association recognized the significance of computers and computing in electro-technology.
[src:alex-dow/american-institute-of-electrical-engineers] The early technical areas of interest of AIEE were electric power, lighting, and wired communications.
[src:alex-dow/american-institute-of-electrical-engineers] Radio and wireless communications became the major focus of a rival organization, the Institute of Radio Engineers (the IRE, established 1912).
[src:alex-dow/american-institute-of-electrical-engineers] The dynamic growth of radio technology and the emergence of the new discipline of electronics in the 1940s led to stiff competition between AIEE and IRE, with IRE showing faster growth in the 1950s and early 1960s, and attracting more students.
[src:alex-dow/american-institute-of-electrical-engineers] In 1957, the IRE, with approximately 55,500 members, surpassed the AIEE in membership size; by 1962 the IRE had 96,500 members to the AIEE's 57,000.
[src:alex-dow/american-institute-of-electrical-engineers] Although the AIEE was a member-volunteer run organization, it relied on a paid staff for daily operations.
[src:alex-dow/american-institute-of-electrical-engineers] The photos that accompanied the article not only included images of the women who worked there, but unusual for the time, also named them.
[src:alex-dow/american-institute-of-electrical-engineers] Female employees of the AIEE included Miss Mary E.
[src:alex-dow/american-institute-of-electrical-engineers] After the AIEE's founding in 1884, its member's badge was created in 1893 by a committee headed by Alexander Graham Bell, AIEE's president from 1891 to 1892.
[src:alex-dow/american-institute-of-electrical-engineers] The badge's logo depicted Benjamin Franklin's kite, representative of the discovery that lightning carried electricity.
[src:alex-dow/american-institute-of-electrical-engineers] The design also showed a winding of gold wire with its midpoints crossed by a galvanometer's indicator, invoking the electrical engineer's Wheatstone bridge.
[src:alex-dow/american-institute-of-electrical-engineers] Ohm's law and the letters "AIEE" were added in gold at the logo's base.
[src:alex-dow/american-institute-of-electrical-engineers] The busy logo design was replaced four years later.
[src:alex-dow/american-institute-of-electrical-engineers] The AIEE and the IRE merged in 1963 to form the Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers (IEEE), in short order becoming the world's largest technical society.
[src:alex-dow/american-society-of-civil-engineers] The **American Society of Civil Engineers** (**ASCE**) is a tax-exempt professional body founded in 1852 to represent members of the civil engineering profession worldwide.
[src:alex-dow/american-society-of-civil-engineers] Headquartered in Reston, Virginia, it is the oldest national engineering society in the United States.
[src:alex-dow/american-society-of-civil-engineers] Its constitution was based on the older Boston Society of Civil Engineers from 1848.
[src:alex-dow/american-society-of-civil-engineers] ASCE is dedicated to the advancement of the science and profession of civil engineering and the enhancement of human welfare through the activities of society members.
[src:alex-dow/american-society-of-civil-engineers] It has more than 143,000 members in 177 countries.
[src:alex-dow/american-society-of-civil-engineers] Its mission is to provide essential value to members, their careers, partners, and the public; facilitate the advancement of technology; encourage and provide the tools for lifelong learning; promote professionalism and the profession; develop and support civil engineers.
[src:alex-dow/american-society-of-civil-engineers] The first serious and documented attempts to organize civil engineers as a professional society in the newly created United States were in the early 19th century.
[src:alex-dow/american-society-of-civil-engineers] Later, in 1834, an American trade periodical, the "American Railroad Journal," advocated for a similar national organization of civil engineers.
[src:alex-dow/american-society-of-civil-engineers] On December 17, 1838, a petition started circulating asking civil engineers to meet in 1839 in Baltimore, Maryland, to organize a permanent society of civil engineers.
[src:alex-dow/american-society-of-civil-engineers] Prior to that, thirteen notable civil engineers largely identifiable as being from New York, Pennsylvania, or Maryland met in Philadelphia.
[src:alex-dow/american-society-of-civil-engineers] Forty engineers actually appeared at the February 1839 meeting in Baltimore, including J.
[src:alex-dow/american-society-of-civil-engineers] Edgar Thomson (Future Chief Engineer and later President of the Pennsylvania Railroad), Wright, Roberts, Edward Miller, and the Maryland engineers Isaac Trimble and Benjamin Henry Latrobe II and attendees from as far as Massachusetts, Illinois, and Louisiana.
[src:alex-dow/american-society-of-civil-engineers] Miller later ascribed the failure to the difficulties of assembling members due to available means for traveling in the country at the time.
[src:alex-dow/american-society-of-civil-engineers] That journal continued discussion on forming an engineers' organization from 1839 thru 1843 serving its own self-interests in advocating its journal as a replacement for a professional society but to no avail.
[src:alex-dow/american-society-of-civil-engineers] During the 1840s, professional organizations continued to develop and organize in the United States.
[src:alex-dow/american-society-of-civil-engineers] During this same period of association incorporations in the 1840s, attempts were again made at organizing an American engineer association.
[src:alex-dow/american-society-of-civil-engineers] They succeeded at first with the Boston Society of Civil Engineers, organized in 1848, and then in October 1852, with an effort to organize a Society of Civil Engineers and Architects in New York.
[src:alex-dow/american-society-of-civil-engineers] Craven, Chief Engineer of the Croton Aqueduct and future ASCE president, the meeting resolved to incorporate the society under the name "American Society of Civil Engineers And Architects".
[src:alex-dow/american-society-of-civil-engineers] The founding meeting was held on November 5, 1852, in the offices of the Croton Aqueduct Department at the Rotunda in City Hall Park, Manhattan.
[src:alex-dow/american-society-of-civil-engineers] Membership eligibility was restricted to "civil, geological, mining and mechanical Engineers, architects, and other persons who, by profession, are interested in the advancement of science." James Laurie was elected the society's first president.
[src:alex-dow/american-society-of-civil-engineers] At an early meeting of the Board of Direction in 1852, instructions were given for the incorporation of the "American Society of Civil Engineers and Architects" but this was the proper steps were never taken, and therefore this name never legally belonged to the association.
[src:alex-dow/american-society-of-civil-engineers] The ASCE held its first meetings at the Croton Aqueduct Department building in City Hall Park.
[src:alex-dow/american-society-of-civil-engineers] The meetings only went through 1855 and with the advent of the American Civil War, the society suspended its activities.
[src:alex-dow/american-society-of-civil-engineers] The next meeting was more than twelve years later in 1867.
[src:alex-dow/american-society-of-civil-engineers] A number of the original founders, such as James Laurie, J.W.
[src:alex-dow/american-society-of-civil-engineers] Talcott, were at this meeting and were dedicated to the objective of resuscitating the society.
[src:alex-dow/american-society-of-civil-engineers] They also planned to put the society on a more permanent footing and elect fifty-four new members.
[src:alex-dow/american-society-of-civil-engineers] With success in that effort, the young engineering society passed a resolution noting that its preservation was mainly due to the persevering efforts of its first president, James Laurie.
[src:alex-dow/american-society-of-civil-engineers] The address of President James Pugh Kirkwood delivered at that meeting in 1867 was the first publication of the society, appearing in Volume 1 of *Transactions*, bearing date of 1872.
[src:alex-dow/american-society-of-civil-engineers] On March 4, 1868, by a vote of 17 to 4, the name was changed to "American Society of Civil Engineers", but it was not until April 17, 1877, that the lack of incorporation was discovered and the proper steps taken to remedy the defect.
[src:alex-dow/american-society-of-civil-engineers] The society was then chartered and incorporated in New York state.
[src:alex-dow/american-society-of-civil-engineers] The reconvened ASCE met at the Chamber of Commerce of the State of New York until 1875 when the society moved to 4 East 23rd Street.
[src:alex-dow/american-society-of-civil-engineers] The ASCE moved again in 1877 to 104 East 20th Street and in 1881 to 127 East 23rd Street.
[src:alex-dow/american-society-of-civil-engineers] The ASCE commissioned a new headquarters at 220 West 57th Street in 1895.
[src:alex-dow/american-society-of-civil-engineers] The building was completed in 1897 and served as the society's headquarters until 1917 when the ASCE moved to the Engineering Societies' Building.
[src:alex-dow/american-society-of-civil-engineers] Nora Stanton Barney was among the first women in the United States to earn a civil engineering degree, graduating from Cornell University in 1905.
[src:alex-dow/american-society-of-civil-engineers] In the same year, she was accepted as a junior member of the organization and began work for the New York City Board of Water Supply.
[src:alex-dow/american-society-of-civil-engineers] She was the first female member of ASCE, where she was allowed to be a junior member, but was denied advancement to associate member in 1916 because of her gender.
[src:alex-dow/american-society-of-civil-engineers] In 2015, she was posthumously advanced to ASCE Fellow status.
[src:alex-dow/american-society-of-civil-engineers] ASCE's headquarters relocated to the Engineering Societies' Building in 1917; additional floors were added on top of the building to accommodate the society's new offices.
[src:alex-dow/american-society-of-civil-engineers] The weight of the extra stories could not be supported on the existing pilings, so four new steel columns were constructed through the structure, supported directly on the bedrock.
[src:alex-dow/american-society-of-civil-engineers] In 1961, ASCE's headquarters moved from the Engineering Societies' Building to the United Engineering Center, a new skyscraper built for twenty different engineering societies across from the headquarters of the United Nations.
[src:alex-dow/american-society-of-civil-engineers] In 1996, ASCE relocated its headquarters from New York City to Reston, Virginia.
[src:alex-dow/american-society-of-civil-engineers] The relocation to the Washington metropolitan area was made to bring ASCE's headquarters closer to the legislative branch of the federal government and also reduced operating costs.
[src:alex-dow/american-society-of-civil-engineers] In 1999, the ASCE elected the top-ten "civil engineering achievements that had the greatest positive impact on life in the 20th century" in "broad categories".
[src:alex-dow/american-society-of-civil-engineers] Monuments of the Millennium were a "combination of technical engineering achievement, courage and inspiration, and a dramatic influence on the development of [their] communities".
[src:alex-dow/american-society-of-civil-engineers] ASCE stated that dissemination of technical and professional information to the civil engineering profession was a major goal of the society.
[src:alex-dow/american-society-of-civil-engineers] They also publish an online bibliographic database, conference proceedings, standards, manuals of practice, and technical reports.
[src:alex-dow/american-society-of-civil-engineers] The ASCE Library contains 470+ e-books and standards, some with chapter-level access and no restrictive DRM, and 600+ online proceedings.
[src:alex-dow/american-society-of-civil-engineers] Each year, more than 55,000 engineers earn continuing education units (CEUs) and/or professional development hours (PDHs) by participating in ASCE's continuing education programs.
[src:alex-dow/american-society-of-civil-engineers] ASCE hosts more than 15 annual and specialty conferences, over 200 continuing education seminars and more than 300 live web seminars.
[src:alex-dow/american-society-of-civil-engineers] Meetings include "...committees, task forces, focus groups, workshops and seminars designed to bring together civil engineering experts either from specific fields or those with a broad range of experience and skills.
[src:alex-dow/american-society-of-civil-engineers] The engineering programs division directly advances the science of engineering by delivering technical content for ASCE's publications, conferences and continuing education programs.
[src:alex-dow/american-society-of-civil-engineers] It consists of eight discipline-specific institutes, four technical divisions, and six technical councils.
[src:alex-dow/american-society-of-civil-engineers] The work is accomplished by over 600 technical committees with editorial responsibility for 28 of ASCE's 33 journals.
[src:alex-dow/american-society-of-civil-engineers] On an annual basis, the division conducts more than twelve congresses and specialty conferences.
[src:alex-dow/american-society-of-civil-engineers] As a founding society of ANSI and accredited standards development organization, ASCE committees use an established and audited process to produce consensus standards under a program supervised by the society's Codes and Standards Committee.
[src:alex-dow/american-society-of-civil-engineers] (CEC), affiliated with ASCE, has been established to support specialty certification academies for civil engineering specialties and is accredited by the Council of Engineering and Scientific Specialty Boards (CESB).
[src:alex-dow/american-society-of-civil-engineers] CEC also handles safety certification for state, municipal, and federal buildings, formerly the province of the now-defunct Building Security Council.
[src:alex-dow/american-society-of-civil-engineers] The Committee on Critical Infrastructure (CCI) provides vision and guidance on ASCE activities related to critical infrastructure resilience, including planning, design, construction, O&M, and event mitigation, response and recovery.
[src:alex-dow/american-society-of-civil-engineers] Certification is the recognition of attaining advanced knowledge and skills in a specialty area of civil engineering.
[src:alex-dow/american-society-of-civil-engineers] ASCE offers certifications for engineers who demonstrate advanced knowledge and skills in their area of engineering.
[src:alex-dow/american-society-of-civil-engineers] Michel Award for Industry Advancement of Research and the Charles Pankow Award for innovation, 12 scholarships and fellowships for student members.
[src:alex-dow/american-society-of-civil-engineers] Created in 1968 by ASCE's Sanitary Engineering Division, the Wesley W.
[src:alex-dow/american-society-of-civil-engineers] Horner award is named after former ASCE President Wesley W.
[src:alex-dow/american-society-of-civil-engineers] Horner, and given to a recently peer reviewed published paper in the fields of hydrology, urban drainage, or sewerage.
[src:alex-dow/american-society-of-civil-engineers] Special consideration is given to private practice engineering work that is recognized as a valuable contribution to the field of environmental engineering.
[src:alex-dow/american-society-of-civil-engineers] The Lifetime Achievement Award has been presented annually since 1999 and recognizes five different individual leaders.
[src:alex-dow/american-society-of-civil-engineers] One award is present in each category of design, construction, government, education, and management.
[src:alex-dow/american-society-of-civil-engineers] In July 1946, the Board of Direction authorized annual awards on recommendation by the society's Committee on Research to stimulate research in civil engineering.
[src:alex-dow/american-society-of-civil-engineers] Alberta Reed Huber endowed these prizes in honor of her husband, Walter L.
[src:alex-dow/american-society-of-civil-engineers] The Huber Prize is considered the highest level mid-career research prize in civil engineering and is awarded for outstanding achievements and contributions in research with respect to all disciplines of civil engineering.
[src:alex-dow/american-society-of-civil-engineers] The LTPP International Data Analysis Contest is an annual data analysis contest held by the ASCE in collaboration with the Federal Highway Administration (FHWA).
[src:alex-dow/american-society-of-civil-engineers] The participants utilize Long-Term Pavement Performance Program (LTPP) data as part of their analysis.
[src:alex-dow/american-society-of-civil-engineers] At the instigation of the former students of Nathan Mortimore Newmark, the Nathan M.
[src:alex-dow/american-society-of-civil-engineers] Newmark Medal was established in 1975 by the Engineering Mechanics Institute and Structural Engineering Institute of the American Society of Civil Engineers (ASCE) in honor of his contributions in structural engineering and mechanics.
[src:alex-dow/american-society-of-civil-engineers] The medal is given to an ASCE member whose outstanding contributions in structural mechanics have substantially strengthened the scientific base of structural engineering, documented in the form of papers or other written presentations.
[src:alex-dow/american-society-of-civil-engineers] Nominations are made once a year and due on November 1.
[src:alex-dow/american-society-of-civil-engineers] The foundation board of directors has seven persons and its bylaws require that four of the seven directors must be ASCE officers as well and the ASCE executive director and chief financial officer must also be ASCE employees.
[src:alex-dow/american-society-of-civil-engineers] The foundation's support is most often to ASCE's charitable, educational and scientific programs.
[src:alex-dow/american-society-of-civil-engineers] The foundation's largest program is supporting three strategic areas; lifelong learning and leadership, advocacy for infrastructure investment and the role of civil engineers in sustainable practices.
[src:alex-dow/american-society-of-civil-engineers] In 2014, this foundation's support in these areas was almost US$4 million.
[src:alex-dow/american-society-of-civil-engineers] ASCE provides peer reviews at the request of public agencies and projects as a "means to improve the management and quality of [public agency] services and thus better protect the public health and safety with which they are entrusted".
[src:alex-dow/american-society-of-civil-engineers] After the 2005 levee failures in Greater New Orleans, the commander of the U.S.
[src:alex-dow/american-society-of-civil-engineers] Lawrence Roth, deputy executive director of the ASCE led the ERP development, served as the panel's chief of staff and facilitated its interaction with IPET.
[src:alex-dow/american-society-of-civil-engineers] The expert panel's role was to provide an independent technical review of the IPET's activities and findings, as stated at a National Research Council meeting in New Orleans: "an independent review panel ensure[s] that the outcome is a robust, credible and defensible performance evaluation".
[src:alex-dow/american-society-of-civil-engineers] Gen Strock gave all expert review panel members an Outstanding Civilian Service Medals.
[src:alex-dow/american-society-of-civil-engineers] On June 1, 2007, the ASCE issued its expert review panel report, and an accompanying press release.
[src:alex-dow/american-society-of-civil-engineers] The corps acknowledged receiving a copy of the letter and refused to comment until the ASCE's Committee on Professional Conduct (CPC) had commented on the complaint.
[src:alex-dow/american-society-of-civil-engineers] It took over a year for the ASCE to announce the results of the CPC.
[src:alex-dow/american-society-of-civil-engineers] On November 14, 2007, ASCE announced that U.S.
[src:alex-dow/american-society-of-civil-engineers] (ret), would lead an independent task force of outside experts to review how ASCE participated in engineering studies of national significance.
[src:alex-dow/american-society-of-civil-engineers] ASCE President David Mongan said the review was to address criticism of ASCE´s role in assisting the Army Corps of Engineers-sponsored investigation of Katrina failures.
[src:alex-dow/american-society-of-civil-engineers] Mongan assured citizens of metro New Orleans in a letter to the *Times Picayune*, that ASCE took "this matter very seriously and that appropriate actions are being taken".
[src:alex-dow/american-society-of-civil-engineers] The panel recommended in results released on September 12, 2008, that ASCE should immediately take steps to remove the potential for conflict of interest in its participation in post-disaster engineering studies.
[src:alex-dow/american-society-of-civil-engineers] It concluded that ASCE should draw up an ethics policy to eliminate questions of possible conflicts of interest.
[src:alex-dow/american-society-of-civil-engineers] On April 6, 2009, an internal probe with the ASCE issued a report that ordered a retraction of the ASCE's June 1, 2007, press release.
[src:alex-dow/american-society-of-civil-engineers] On November 5, 2007, New Orleans–based grassroots group *Levees.org* led by Sandy Rosenthal criticized the ASCE's close relationship with the United States Army Corps of Engineers in a spoof online public service announcement.
[src:alex-dow/american-society-of-civil-engineers] On November 12, 2007, the ASCE asked Levees.org to remove the video from the internet, threatening the organization with legal action if it did not comply.
[src:alex-dow/american-society-of-civil-engineers] On November 13, the Times-Picayune posted the video on its website.
[src:alex-dow/american-society-of-civil-engineers] In March 2008, Levees.org announced that records obtained under the Freedom of Information Act revealed that as early October 2005, the Army Corps of Engineers had directed and later paid the ASCE more than $1.1 million for its peer review (Grant Number: W912HZ-06-1-0001).
[src:alex-dow/american-society-of-civil-engineers] The grant also paid for a series of misleading ASCE presentations attempting to shift blame away from the corps and onto local levee officials.
[src:alex-dow/american-society-of-civil-engineers] Members of the ASCE are forbidden from making false or exaggerated statements and also from making statements for an interested party unless this is disclosed.
[src:alex-dow/american-society-of-civil-engineers] Levees.org claimed the records showed how the external peer review would be done in four phases: Phase 1 was research and analysis on the performance of the levees, floodwalls and other important structures.
[src:alex-dow/american-society-of-civil-engineers] Phase 2 was provision of information on the current system to prevent future flooding.
[src:alex-dow/american-society-of-civil-engineers] Phase 3 was provision of information to evaluate alternative approaches to flood protection.
[src:alex-dow/american-society-of-civil-engineers] Phase 4 was transfer information and knowledge gained to a broader audience within Corps and its consultancy community to communicate lessons learned.
[src:alex-dow/american-society-of-civil-engineers] The group claimed that these records were proof that ASCE's routine powerpoint presentation from 2007 and 2008 were a public relations campaign to repair the corps' reputation.
[src:alex-dow/american-society-of-civil-engineers] ASCE officials responded that ASCE paid for the powerpoint presentations itself and had not used USACE grant money for that purpose.
[src:alex-dow/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] Founded as an engineering society focused on mechanical engineering in North America, ASME is today multidisciplinary and global.
[src:alex-dow/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] ASME has over 85,000 members in more than 135 countries worldwide.
[src:alex-dow/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] ASME was founded in 1880 in response to numerous steam boiler pressure vessel failures by Alexander Lyman Holley, Henry Rossiter Worthington, John Edison Sweet and Matthias N.
[src:alex-dow/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] Forney, with Robert Henry Thurston as the society's founding president.
[src:alex-dow/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] Known for setting codes and standards for mechanical devices, ASME conducts one of the world's largest technical publishing operations.
[src:alex-dow/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] It holds numerous technical conferences and hundreds of professional development courses each year and sponsors numerous outreach and educational programs.
[src:alex-dow/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] Ned Djilali and Georgia Tech president and woman engineer supporter Blake R Van Leer were executive members.
[src:alex-dow/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] Kate Gleason and Lydia Weld were the first two women members.
[src:alex-dow/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] ASME is one of the oldest standards-developing organizations in America.
[src:alex-dow/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] It produces approximately 600 codes and standards covering many technical areas, such as fasteners, plumbing fixtures, elevators, pipelines, and power plant systems and components.
[src:alex-dow/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] ASME's standards are developed by committees of subject matter experts using an open, consensus-based process.
[src:alex-dow/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] Many ASME standards are cited by government agencies as tools to meet their regulatory objectives.
[src:alex-dow/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] ASME standards are therefore voluntary, unless the standards have been incorporated into a legally binding business contract or incorporated into regulations enforced by an authority having jurisdiction, such as a federal, state, or local government agency.
[src:alex-dow/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] ASME's standards are used in more than 100 countries and have been translated into numerous languages.
[src:alex-dow/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] The largest ASME standard, both in size and in the number of volunteers involved in its preparation, is the ASME Boiler and Pressure Vessel Code (BPVC).
[src:alex-dow/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] The BPVC provides rules for the design, fabrication, installation, inspection, care, and use of boilers, pressure vessels, and nuclear components.
[src:alex-dow/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] The code also includes standards on materials, welding and brazing procedures and qualifications, nondestructive examination, and nuclear in-service inspection.
[src:alex-dow/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] In addition to academic journals, since 1880 the ASME has also published the magazine *Mechanical Engineering*.
[src:alex-dow/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] This means the nominees need not be professional educators.
[src:alex-dow/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] (1879–1964), an ASME Member and professor of mechanical engineering and head of the department at the Polytechnic Institute of Brooklyn, established the Medal.
[src:alex-dow/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] ASME runs several annual E-Fests, or Engineering Festivals, taking the place of the Student Professional Development Conference (SPDC) series.
[src:alex-dow/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] In addition to the Human Powered Vehicle Challenge (HPVC), the Innovative Additive Manufacturing 3D Challenge (IAM3D), the Student Design Competition, and the Old Guard Competition, there are also talks, interactive workshops, and entertainment.
[src:alex-dow/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] These events allows students to network with working engineers, host contests, and promote ASME's benefits to students as well as professionals.
[src:alex-dow/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] E-Fests are held in four regions in the United States and internationally—western U.S, eastern U.S., Asia Pacific, and South America—with the E-Fest location for each region changing every year.
[src:alex-dow/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] ASME holds a variety of competitions every year for engineering students from around the world.
[src:alex-dow/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] ASME has four key offices in the United States, including its headquarters operation in New York, N.Y., and three international offices in Beijing, China; Brussels, Belgium, and New Delhi, India.
[src:alex-dow/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] ASME has two institutes and 32 technical divisions within its organizational structure.
[src:alex-dow/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] In 1982, ASME was found to be the first non-profit organization to in violation of the Sherman Antitrust Act.
[src:alex-dow/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] The United States Supreme Court found the organization liable for more than $6 million in *American Society of Mechanical Engineers v.
